2.  Research about How API Works
What Is an API?
API stands for Application Programming Interface.
It‚Äôs like a messenger that allows different software systems (apps, servers, devices) to talk to each other.
________________________________________
üö¶ Real-Life Analogy:
Imagine you're at a restaurant:
‚Ä¢	You are the user/client.
‚Ä¢	The kitchen is the server.
‚Ä¢	The waiter is the API.
You (the client) don‚Äôt go into the kitchen‚Äîyou tell the waiter (API) what you want (e.g., "one burger").
The waiter takes your request to the kitchen and brings the food back.
You don‚Äôt care how the kitchen made it‚Äîyou just get what you asked for.
________________________________________
How an API Works (Step by Step)
1. Client Makes a Request
    A client (web browser, mobile app, etc.) sends a request to the API.
	The request includes:
	A URL (the endpoint)
	A method (like GET, POST)
	Sometimes data (like login info)
	Headers (e.g., for authentication)

________________________________________
2. API Receives the Request
‚Ä¢	The API receives the request and processes it.
‚Ä¢	It might:
o	Query a database
o	Talk to another service
o	Apply logic
________________________________________
3. API Sends a Response
‚Ä¢	After processing, the API returns a response to the client.
‚Ä¢	The response usually includes:
o	A status code (200 OK, 404 Not Found, etc.)
o	Data (usually in JSON or XML)

________________________________________
Common API Types
Type	Description	Example
REST	Web-based, uses HTTP methods	GET /users/1
SOAP	XML-based, older enterprise APIs	Used in banks, legacy systems
GraphQL	Flexible query API from Facebook	Get exactly what you need
gRPC	High-performance binary API	Used in microservices
WebSocket	Real-time two-way communication	Chat apps, live updates
________________________________________
What About Security?
APIs usually require authentication, such as:
‚Ä¢	API keys
‚Ä¢	OAuth tokens
‚Ä¢	JWTs (JSON Web Tokens)
This ensures only authorized clients can access or modify data.
________________________________________
Example Use Cases
‚Ä¢	Weather app fetching forecast
‚Ä¢	Payment system sending transaction
‚Ä¢	Mobile app logging in a user
‚Ä¢	Smartwatch syncing health data
________________________________________
TL;DR
An API is a bridge that lets different software talk to each other.
You (the client) ask for something, and the API delivers it from the server‚Äîclean, structured, and secure.
