7. what is the max length of the URL?
The maximum length of a URL depends on the context (such as the browser or server), but here are the general rules:
1. Browsers
‚Ä¢	Internet Explorer (IE): The maximum URL length is 2,083 characters.
‚Ä¢	Modern browsers (like Chrome, Firefox, Safari): Generally support URLs up to 32,768 characters or more, but this can vary.
2. Web Servers
‚Ä¢	Apache: By default, limits request line (including URL) to 8,192 bytes, but this is configurable.
‚Ä¢	Nginx: Default limit is 4,096 bytes for the request line, also configurable.
‚Ä¢	IIS (Microsoft): Has a limit of 16,384 characters by default.
3. Practical Recommendation
‚Ä¢	Keep URLs under 2,000 characters for maximum compatibility across browsers and servers.
‚Ä¢	For URLs in GET requests, anything over 2,048 characters can be problematic depending on the environment.
4. RFC 3986 (Standard)
‚Ä¢	Technically, there is no defined limit in the specification, but implementations impose their own limits.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
8. How or when the IP address update of our mobile or laptop device (optional extra point)
mobile or laptop‚Äôs IP address can change (or update) depending on where, how, and when you connect to a network. Here's a clear explanation of how and when your IP address updates:
1. When You Change Networks
Whenever you connect to a new Wi-Fi or mobile network, you‚Äôre assigned a new IP address:
‚Ä¢	At home ‚Üí You get a local IP from your router (e.g., 192.168.x.x) and a public IP from your ISP.
‚Ä¢	At a caf√© or public Wi-Fi ‚Üí You get a different local IP from that network.
‚Ä¢	Using mobile data ‚Üí Your mobile carrier gives you a different (public or NATed) IP.
 IP updates:
‚Ä¢	Instantly upon connecting to the new network.
________________________________________
2. When DHCP Lease Expires (on Wi-Fi)
‚Ä¢	Your device gets an IP address from a DHCP server (usually your router).
‚Ä¢	This address is only leased temporarily (e.g., for 24 hours).
‚Ä¢	After the lease ends, the IP might be renewed or changed.
IP updates:
‚Ä¢	When DHCP lease expires and a new IP is assigned.
‚Ä¢	You can also force renewal by:
o	Windows: ipconfig /release then ipconfig /renew
o	macOS/Linux: sudo dhclient -r then sudo dhclient
________________________________________
3. When Switching Between Mobile Data and Wi-Fi
‚Ä¢	Mobile data and Wi-Fi have separate IPs.
‚Ä¢	Switching between them instantly changes your IP address.
________________________________________
4. Restarting Your Router (Sometimes)
Restarting a home router or modem may cause your external/public IP to change (if your ISP uses dynamic IPs). But some ISPs give you a static IP which doesn't change.
________________________________________
5. Using VPNs or Proxies
A VPN gives your device a completely different IP (usually from another location or country).
‚Ä¢	Disconnecting the VPN will revert to your regular IP.
________________________________________
6. Manually Changing IP
You can manually configure a different local IP (e.g., 192.168.1.55) in:
‚Ä¢	Wi-Fi settings ‚Üí Advanced ‚Üí Static IP (on mobile or laptop)
‚Ä¢	Network settings in Control Panel or macOS preferences
________________________________________
Summary Table
Scenario	IP Change?	How?
Switching Wi-Fi networks	‚úÖ	New DHCP IP from new router
Mobile Data On/Off	‚úÖ	IP from mobile carrier
DHCP Lease Expired	‚úÖ	May renew or change IP
Restarting Router	‚ùì	Sometimes changes public IP
VPN On/Off	‚úÖ	Changes to VPN-assigned IP
Manually Set IP	‚úÖ	Changes local IP only


